[!INFO] AKA Berger disease
IgA nephropathy is also called Berger disease.

Lewy Body Pale substantia nigra

Mnemonic: "Long sexy eye lashes" - long ciliary nerve carries sympathetic fibers.

Facial nerve anatomy

  • Motor efferents to facial muscles
    • and Posterior auricular nerve and branch to posterior belly of digastric and stylohyoid muscle
  • Parasympathetic efferents lacrimal glands, submandibular glands and sublingual glands (but not the parotid gland?) - via the greater petrosal nerve and chorda tympani
  • Afferent taste fibers from front 2/3 of the tongue - via the chorda tympani
  • Somatic afferents from the pinna and external auditory canal.

causes of bilateral facial nerve palsy

[!TIP] Mnemonic : LGBT sex

  1. Lyme disease
  2. Guillain Barre syndrome
  3. Bell's Palsy (bialteral)
  4. [[Tuberculosis]] / Tumours (see 7)
  5. [[Sarcoidosis]]
  6. ?botulinum toxin
  7. Bilateral acoustic neuroma (NF type 2) or pontine tumours affecting both cranial nerve nuclei.

Q 15: Aortic stenosis

[!INFO] Aortic Stenosis Murmur intensity does NOT correlate with severity.
However, in MR and AR, murmur loudness does correlate with severity.

Causes of Aortic stenosis

Commonest in people < 65 - bicuspid aortic valve.
Commonest in people > 65 - age related calficication.

Other causes:

  • Supravalvar - william's syndrome
  • Subvalvular - HOCM
  • Post rheumatic disease.

Management:

Symptomatology is the main determinant of need for management.
Even in asymptomatic patients, the the pressure gradient is > 40 mmHg, treatment may be needed.
Options:

  • Aortic valve replacement is TOC for young patients. (TAVR for patients with high operative risk)
    • [[INRTargetprostheticValves.png]]
  • Balloon valvuloplasty - children or adults not fit for surgery.

Types of diastolic murmurs

[!WARNING] DO NOT combine non-dihydropyridine CCBs with beta blockers
i.e never combine verapamil / diltiazem with beta blockers -> risk of heart block

Medication is used to

  1. releive symptoms -> antianginal medications

  2. prevent progression ->

    1. All patients should be on aspirin and statin.
     1. rate liming Non-dihydropyridines are preferred when used as monotherapy.
    1. Longer acting dihydropyridines are used:
      1. Amlodipine or modified release nifedipine.

  • If the patient's angina isn't controlled on two first line anti-anginals, they are a candidate for revascularization. While they are waiting for revascularization, a second line antianginal can be added. (or if revascularization isn't an option)

  • "Classically extra-renal manifestations are seen in severe disease".

  • Most commonly hepatic and cardiovascular.

    • "hepatic" are the commonest extrarenal manifestations - 70%.

  • Cardiovascular: Mitral valve prolapse.

    • But also MR, TR, Aortic root dilation, aortic dissection

Ventricular interdependance = reduced LV volume which occurs when RV is distended by a sudden increased in preload (eg. Inspiration)

[!TIP] Mnemonic: TAMPAX
TAMponade - Pulsus paradoxus and X descent are seen.
Constrictive pericarditis - C and K -> Kussmaul sign present.

Pathophysiology Pathophysiology
Left and Right ventricular diastolic pressure and left and right atrial pressures (PCWP) all rise to match the pericardial pressure. ?Greatly increased ventricular interdependance
Greatly increased ventricular interdependance is what causes pulsus paradoxus. normal inspiratory decrease in intrathoracic pressure is not transmitted to intracardiac pressures. This effect amplifies inspiratory decreases in pulmonary venous pressure (because plm vein is outside the pericardial sac)

Central cord syndrome

Central cord syndrome occurs most commonly in those who suffer a hyperextension injury. This usually happens with a forward fall while striking the chin and having the neck extend backward at the time of the fall.
Weakness of Upper limbs >> Lower limbs.
Loss of pain and temperature in "cape like" distribution over upper back.
